Turkey is widening diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to enter the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps in Asia, is one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
This is at least what the tour guides tell you.
The building is riding between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking to the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building slightly decaying.
But once inside the office ticket from the vaulted ceiling, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise of what was the most western passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retarded imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of this railway that ran to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is Saudi Arabia today.
But Germany's imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Its isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed
British and dominating forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news about Hyderpasha station, too.
In 1917 an ammo train broke out destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then he has slowly gone into decay, largely surpassed by history.
But nowadays, this railway outlet for Anatolia and all the points to the east, serve - at least symbolically - to highlight the ever-greater diplomatic horizons of Turkey.
The ruling party of Justice and Development - the AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Its isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed away.
Now there is a new policy of commitment.
The Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I embarked on the bed car for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the main foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish congressman Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bumpy run along the slopes that produced the ancient world cadences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state willing to turn my back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, more notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by commercial centers means built and confections of power, where managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make early morning contracts.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost every other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
"The purpose of the foreign policy party is now to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbours.
Cold war was an anomaly," he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today he has to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't about one or the other.
It's got to be both.
"But surely at some point, " I ask, " will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want to face that choice."
Then he emphasized a point that almost all those with whom I spoke here have recited by heart: the ties of not only the Middle East, but also the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, Europe as a whole can metaphorically travel those railway lines east through Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpasha station, after another night in white, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to find that Europe's medium-oriental ambitions can now, to a large extent, be in the hands of Turkey.
And while I wait at the ferry terminal that takes me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that those days Turkey has always been called "the sick man of Europe."
Then at least there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent was to make claims on this fascinating country.
