The "bee car" to avoid collisions
In the context of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, for example, takes the flight of bees, can avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, or the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Centre of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C constitutes an extension of the Security Shield of four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicles of the manufacturer.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that is very similar to the Nissan security shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of the bees, able to see in all directions with an angle above 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what they called a localization laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism detects the obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two metres and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately prevents collision.
"When it detects an obstacle, the small robot imitates the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at a right or greater angle to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape manoeuvre is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot turn upwards or downwards, or even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which they can turn its wheels and not using endless directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to act from this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers ahead, so it can work without interruptions and with only a couple of dozen KBs of memory.
This may surprise us, but we're not talking about memory gigabytes, or mega gigabytes."
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the instant prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to his destination avoiding the obstacles present in the path.
