Rafael Correa à Quito, please.
Found the republic on a socialism right in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave a voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since, according to official results, 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, on a vote basis of 80%.
According to these results, the "no" was 28%, while 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were blank.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should get half of the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the exit of the polling stations and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced an overwhelming victory of the "yes," placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution in the night between Sunday and Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously," he assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians within the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers south-west of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The ballot, which took place calmly in accordance with the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OEA), was based on a text of 444 points to consolidate the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserving to it the "planification of development" of a country that lives essentially of the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently of their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants greater power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year term, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced its intention to take advantage of this amendment and to renew its candidacy for a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also states the gratuitousness of health and education services, which the President has begun to promote in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US drug operations.
The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts kidnapped ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive in the desert for ten days were brought back on Monday afternoon, safe and sound, in the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they were liberated in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at the military base of Almaza, near Cairo International Airport, around 3:30 p.m., on a special plane.
Aboard a helicopter, they were transferred immediately, without being able to give any interviews to the press, to the hospital in Maadi, a residential outskirts of Cairo, to be subjected to analysis.
They enjoy "good health" and no ransom has been paid "to the kidnappers," said the Egyptian Minister of Tourism, Zoheir Garanna, on the runway.
Kidnapped on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous, the agency organizer of the safari.
One Egyptian security officer said that 30 members of the special forces, on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night, just before dawn.
"There were shots fired, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled," said the person responsible who requested to remain anonymous.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where German and Italian commandos would support them.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces.
We must admit that if we have achieved this result it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, of the special forces," he said, without adding any further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on which the kidnappers were found and killed six of them, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and captured two of them.
According to the army, the kidnappers would be linked to a Darfur rebel organization, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), which was immediately denied by the Sudan Liberation Movement.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
On the front page a debate on the financing of culture on which the current election campaign focuses.
All the better.
But a part of our cultural life is always in the shadows.
Who will decide to denounce the miserable sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical places that hunger?
What politician dares remind the federal government that he is neglecting monuments and property buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government pays three and a half million euros for the restoration of the castle of Chinon, in the Loire valley?
With our American neighbours, it is the Constitution that affirms that the protection of heritage is part of national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, by every political authority and by every government department, and all this by mutual agreement.
At least 40 000 volunteers in Quebec, in the Federation of Historical Companies of Quebec, are grouped into 211 companies for the preservation of historical, genealogical, archives and assets, and preserve private archives and archaeological sites.
They are the ones who often defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision-making bodies attack with their bulldozers our forgotten remains and cemeteries.
When will the right space be reserved for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help through partial nationalisation the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which ended up in trouble first in Europe due to the crisis in the American credit market: the three nations will provide € 11.2 billion to the financial institution - insurance with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and Holland agreed at the highest level on the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties facing the international financial market for more than a year is that of the Fortis bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard may constitute a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night all three states will determine almost half (49%) of the bank's share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including, first of all, the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis' actions began with a vertical collapse, serious signals of crisis of the institute were then presented in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
Bank shares on Friday fell by almost 12%, the lowest point for 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
Considering the current stock prices, the entire capital value of the group is around €14 billion, but according to the bank's managers this value is not real.
The company summit blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday the title slowly resumed to rise.
On Friday Filip Dierckx has been appointed new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has submitted a worthy offer.
The Belgian Government had previously assured that investors should not be afraid of losing money.
Among the bank's customers there was no panic, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent subsidiaries and has also purchased leasing companies.
The fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurers often refuse to enter into an insurance contract on the basis of personal medical data.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the henhouse to the fox," writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick as the author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies shall make the insurance fee and the amount due in the event of claims to the health of the customer and if they consider the risk to be too high, they shall not conclude the insurance.
A long time ago the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper process: based on the customer's identification code you can easily get information from the pharmacies on which medicines he has bought in the last year and a half and from this the program shows which diseases he suffers and in what health conditions he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is basically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, to the insurer therefore beyond the paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines can be used for several purposes, e.g. some compounds can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the insurance - commercial point of view, is worth as a factor of increase of risk, the first two not.
For the request and processing of data, companies have been formed separately and these, before obtaining from the pharmacies the necessary information, ask for the approval of the patient.
The authorities are now forcing them to do so even if they have not so far imposed fines on negligence.
Some firms have recently also developed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to the drug consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of the patient's state of health.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time the control of use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control competence to companies specializing in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: that's why he has developed a program that links data transmission with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another question is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
So in the end the chickens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
