European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are partners that trade mainly with each other, the agenda of the ninth meeting at the summit was also dominated by this issue, as well as all the other global problems.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit which will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognises the fact that India is becoming a great democratic power to which more voice should be given in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So we did not insist on this issue at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseilles.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as President-in-Office of the Union, José Manuel Barroso, Chairman of the Commission and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade in five years, i.e. to increase to EUR 100 billion.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not too ambitious.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so air traffic can also start in the future.
India would like to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the deal.
The aim is to balance because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted attention to global matters.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms by both sides, and called for a UN conference to be convened.
They urged the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, although both sides had a role in the failure of this.
The EU has confirmed its continued energy and climate programme, which would like to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees on this, as well as on the fact that a global pact should be concluded at the climate conference planned for next year and reduce greenhouse gas production by 50% by 2050.
They also want to curb the rise in food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister will now travel to the French capital where he is preparing to sign a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive a contract worth EUR 20 billion to build Indian nuclear reactors.
According to information from our press agency, the deal would last 15 years.
