The wreck of Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire who died on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, was found.
The wreckage was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the aircraft, however, there were no human remains.
The sheriff of Madeira County, John Anderson, escaped the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is exactly what Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared," he said in a press conference.
The sheriff then pointed out that no human remains were found either in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was reported dead in February.
The U.S. Transport Safety Office (NTSB) reported that a few hours after the shipwreck was sighted, a team of investigators was sent, who then identified the device: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal effects had been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents under the name Fossett, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's research had been interrupted a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of primates.
In 2002, at the sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solitary flight.
Three years later, he traveled the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among his many records, he also flew 15,445 meters high, above the Andes, but with a copilot.
